To support static resources, the request is forwarded via the url redirect filter.  However, the currently logged in user gets lots or is never resolved, meaning these requests come in unauthenticated as far as the code is concerned.  I found this out via a per-user plugin access list plugin I was writing, where I wanted a WebResourceTransformer that generated different content for different users.  Unfortunately, via SAL, I wasn't able to retrieve any user info.  I ended up working around this by using reflection and hacking the user object stored in the session.

The new plugin manager has a big warning above the system plugins saying:

{quote}
These plugins are integral parts of your Confluence system. They cannot be uninstalled. Disabling or removing them will have serious effects, and may render Confluence inoperable. Do not make changes here unless instructed by Atlassian Support. 
{quote}

Many of the plugins can be safely disabled.  The ones that can't should not allow disabling (and in the cases I checked, they don't).  

Aside from being an outright falsehood, there is some danger to the error message, since administrators may enable dangerous plugins they should not enable.

